# CHANGELOG is generated by `bin/changelog render`; fragments are
# bullet snippets (no top-level heading, sometimes `<slug>`
# placeholders) — both trip MD041/MD033 for no real benefit. Per
# arthur-debert/release#234.
CHANGELOG.md
CHANGELOG/
# Changelog-staging files (the "Unreleased" section some repos keep as a
# separate file) are the same class: they lead with an HTML comment / `###`
# rather than a top-level heading (MD041) and accrete bullet fragments. Exempt
# them like CHANGELOG. See docs/references/lint-debt-model.md.
UNRELEASED.md
CHANGELOG_UNRELEASED.md

# CLAUDE.md is agent-instruction content, not published prose — the same
# class as the skills exclude below. release-sync also injects a managed
# orientation block at its top (an HTML-comment-delimited `@.release/...`
# import, release#348), which legitimately makes the first line a comment
# rather than a heading (MD041) and uses inline HTML (MD033). Linting it
# fights the managed block for no real benefit.
CLAUDE.md

# .claude/skills/** and docs/skills/** are agent-authored skill
# documentation. AI-generated markdown often has stylistic quirks
# (in-table section headers, mixed list styles) that are intentional
# for AI consumption but trip strict markdownlint rules. Keep them
# out of the gate; consumers can lint them on demand if they want to.
.claude/skills/
docs/skills/

# Vendored third-party content (e.g. vendor/semver-tool/README.md). Not
# ours to clean; cleaning it churns on upstream updates. Same class as
# the skills exclude above.
vendor/

# mdBook part-title pages: a SUMMARY.md legitimately uses multiple H1
# headings as part titles, which mdBook REQUIRES (converting them to H2
# deletes them from the rendered TOC). That conflicts with MD025
# (single-H1), and the content cannot be "fixed" without breaking the
# book — so SUMMARY.md is excluded fleet-wide. Caught via standout#164.
**/SUMMARY.md

# Test fixture content is DATA, not authored docs: gallery content,
# parser inputs, byte-exact template fixtures, etc. They intentionally
# model raw/varied/malformed input (headingless captions, URL-only
# pages, deliberately broken markdown), so forcing them to pass
# markdownlint corrupts what's under test. Caught via simple-gal#107.
**/fixtures/**
# Generated regression/benchmark corpora are the same DATA class: golden
# converter output (e.g. lex→markdown) that deliberately exercises edge
# cases which by design DON'T produce clean markdown (citation/section-ref
# anchors without in-doc targets, etc.). Linting golden output fights the
# test. Fix the generator (e.g. lex#715), not the fixture. Caught via comms.
**/benchmark/**
